Headlines.Author: Frank Barnako
Headlines.Headline: S&P 500 index clear winner

#text:

    & Poor's 500 Index

funds are beating the returns of 88 percent of U.S. equity
    funds. Kanon Bloch Carre, a Boston-based consultant said its research shows that
    "any fund that hasn't concentrated assets in the 100 biggest companies in the country
    has been lagging. That's where the best performance has been for the past four
    years," Bloomberg news reported. Last year about 25 percent of equity funds
    out-performed the S&P. The S&P 500 has risen 34.08 percent this year, while the
    Russell 200 Index has gained 21.17 percent. The funds that are performing better than the
    S&P 500 this year include Pioneer
    Growth

, Vanguard
    Primecap

    Investors

Headlines.Author: Mary Kennedy
Headlines.Headline: Cocoa sweetened by El Nino

#text:
NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- As bakers use
    more chocolate for holiday goodies, the cocoa grinch, a.k.a. El Niño, is busy melting the world's supply. March
    cocoa

rose 3.1 percent Friday morning, extending Thursday's rally, amid indications
    that Southeast Asian and South American crop yields will be smaller because of the El Niño weather pattern. Southeast Asia is too dry and
    South America is too wet due to unusual weather caused by warming in the Pacific Ocean.
    Cocoa rose on indications that yields may be smaller from most cocoa-producing countries,
    with the exception of the Ivory Coast, due to harsh weather caused by El Niño. In recent trade, March cocoa rose $51.00 to $1,722.00
    per ton on the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Cocoa sweetened by El Nino
